message.content: Since we want to find the cost of buying 600 chocolate candies, and we know that 25 candies cost $\$6$, we can set up a proportion. Let $x$ represent the cost of 600 candies. Setting up a proportion results in the equation $\frac{x}{600}=\frac{6}{25}$. Cross multiplying gives $x\cdot 25=6\cdot 600$. Dividing both sides of the equation by 25 gives $x=\boxed{144}$.
